      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the flax egg",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mix the {{flaxseed-ground}} with the cold {{water}} in a small bowl or cup. Stir well and set aside for at least 5 minutes. The mixture will thicken to a gel. This is the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "flax egg",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpaqcxxy0000rsv421wjeq7x"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " that binds the batter in place of eggs.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mix and bake, 50 to 55 minutes",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 170°C fan. Grease and line a 900 g loaf tin. Whisk the {{plain-flour}}, {{light-brown-sugar}}, {{baking-powder}}, {{bicarbonate-of-soda}}, {{cinnamon-ground}}, {{ginger-ground}}, and {{fine-sea-salt}} together in a large bowl. In a separate bowl, mix the flax egg with the {{vegetable-oil}}, {{oat-milk}}, and {{vanilla-extract}}. Add the wet ingredients to the dry and fold together until almost combined. Add the grated {{carrot}} and {{walnuts}} and fold until evenly distributed. Pour into the tin and bake for 50 to 55 minutes until a skewer inserted in the centre comes out clean.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drizzle and cool",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "While the cake bakes, stir the {{icing-sugar}} into the {{lemon-juice}} to make a thin, pourable glaze. As soon as the cake comes out of the oven, poke all over with a skewer and pour the glaze slowly over the top, letting it soak in. Leave to cool in the tin for 20 minutes before turning out onto a rack.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
